<div xmlns:java="http://xml.apache.org/xslt/java" id="centre_col"><!-- begin original content --><h1>ESSUM33600 - Shares to which
schemes can apply: General pre-emption provisions</h1>
<br>
<p>General pre-emption provisions must be tested:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">in cases with employee pre-emption
restrictions, to ensure that the requirements of paragraph 21(3)(b)
are satisfied (see 
<a href="ESSUM33570.htm">ESSUM33570</a>), and</li>
<li class="filledcircle">in their own right to ensure that they
attach to all shares of the same class (see 
<a href="ESSUM33475.htm">ESSUM33475</a>).</li>
</ul>
<p>For the purposes of paragraph 21(3)(b) the only permitted
difference between the terms regulating the transfer of employee
held shares and those relating to other shares of the same class is
effectively that</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">an employee or director is forced to sell
when he ceases, whereas</li>
<li class="filledcircle">other shareholders may withdraw their
transfer notices if they decide against selling.</li>
</ul>
<p>The general pre-emption provisions usually appear first in the
clauses of the Articles regulating transfers of shares. The most
common format is:</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">any member (shareholder) wishing to sell
or transfer shares gives the company a "transfer notice" indicating
he or she wishes to offer their shares for sale</li>
<li class="filledcircle">the company offers the shares to all other
shareholders at a "fair value" determined by the company's auditors
(see 
<a href="ESSUM33560.htm">ESSUM33560</a>)</li>
<li class="filledcircle">if the shares being offered for sale are
not all taken up by the other members, the vendor shareholder is
usually given the opportunity to offer them to a person of his own
choice.</li>
</ul>
<p>The employee pre-emption provisions (if there are any) then
usually appear after the general pre-emption provisions and</p>
<br>
<ul>
<li class="filledcircle">deem ceasing employees and directors to
have given a transfer notice if one is not actually served within a
specified period, and</li>
<li class="filledcircle">apply all of the preceding general
pre-emption provisions to such compulsory sales by employees and
directors.</li>
</ul>
<p>Some Articles contain, as part of the general pre-emption
provisions, the power to revoke a transfer notice once given. This
is acceptable for the purposes of general pre-emption restrictions
under paragraph 21(1). But care should be taken to ensure that a
compulsory transfer notice served, or deemed to have been served,
under the employee pre-emption procedures cannot be revoked. If
employee pre-emption transfer notices are revocable the
requirements of paragraph 21(2) (a) will not be satisfied &ndash;
(see 
<a href="ESSUM33500.htm">ESSUM33500</a>).
<br>
<br> Some Articles contain an "all or nothing" provision in the
general pre-emption provisions, such that if a buyer is not found
for all of the shares being offered for sale, then none shall be
sold. This is acceptable for the purposes of general pre-emption,
but care should be taken to ensure that it does not apply to the
compulsory sales under the employee pre-emption procedures. If
buyers are only found for part of the holding of a ceasing employee
or director, then that part of the holding must be transferred.
<br>
<br> General pre-emption provisions for offering the vendor's
shares to other persons may give priority rights (of first refusal)
to certain shareholders. There is no objection to this in principle
for the purposes of paragraph 21(3), provided the same procedures
apply for transfers by all shareholders, including employees and
directors. But the priority rights thereby given to other
shareholders may need to be considered for the purposes of
paragraph 21(1) to ensure that they do not result in the scheme
shares being restricted by having lesser rights in comparison (see 
<a href="ESSUM33475.htm">ESSUM33475</a>).</p>
<br>
